@node Installation
@chapter Installation
@cindex installation

This chapter walks you through installing everything Codebud needs on
Arch Linux: system packages, Ollama, the Python virtual environment, and
the Codebud package itself.  If you are on another distribution, the
steps are the same in spirit --- substitute your package manager where
@command{pacman} appears.

@menu
* System Requirements::         What hardware and OS you need.
* System Packages::             Installing Python, Node.js, and build tools.
* Installing Ollama::           Getting the local LLM server.
* Cloning Codebud::             Getting the source code.
* Python Environment::          Creating the virtual environment and installing deps.
* Verifying the Install::       Running a quick sanity check.
@end menu


@node System Requirements
@section System Requirements
@cindex system requirements

@table @strong
@item OS
Arch Linux (rolling).  Other systemd-based distributions work with minor
adjustments.
@item RAM
8 GB minimum (for the 3B model).  16 GB recommended.
@item Disk
~3 GB for the recommended model, plus ~100 MB for the code and venv.
@item CPU
Any modern x86-64.  No GPU required; see @ref{Choosing a Model} for
speed expectations.
@item Network
Required once to install packages and pull the model.  The agent itself
runs fully offline after that.
@end table


@node System Packages
@section System Packages
@cindex pacman
@cindex system packages

First make sure your system is up to date:

@example
sudo pacman -Syu
@end example

Then install the required packages in one command:

@example
sudo pacman -S python python-pip python-virtualenv \
               git curl base-devel nodejs npm
@end example

@table @strong
@item python, python-pip, python-virtualenv
Codebud and all its dependencies are pure Python.
@item git
Required to clone the repository.
@item curl, base-devel
Used when building native extensions (some pip packages compile C code).
@item nodejs, npm
Required for the OpenClaw UI gateway (@pxref{Usage}).
@end table

Verify the key tools are present:

@example
python --version    # expect Python 3.11 or later
git --version
node --version
@end example


@node Installing Ollama
@section Installing Ollama
@cindex Ollama, installation
@cindex AUR

Ollama is the local LLM server.  Codebud sends every prompt to it
over a local HTTP connection.

@subsection Option A --- AUR (recommended on Arch)

If you have an AUR helper installed, use it so that Ollama is managed
by pacman and upgrades cleanly:

@example
yay -S ollama
# or:
paru -S ollama
@end example

@subsection Option B --- Official installer script

If you do not use the AUR, the official script works on any distribution:

@example
curl -fsSL https://ollama.com/install.sh | sh
@end example

This installs @file{/usr/local/bin/ollama} and optionally a systemd unit.

@strong{Note:} the AUR package is preferred on Arch because it integrates
with @command{pacman} for upgrades, handles the service unit correctly,
and does not require running an untrusted shell script as root.

@subsection Starting Ollama

After installation, start the server:

@example
# One-off (for testing):
ollama serve

# Permanent (recommended):
sudo systemctl enable --now ollama
@end example

Verify it is running:

@example
curl http://localhost:11434/api/tags
@end example

You should see a JSON response.  If you get @samp{Connection refused},
the server is not running --- start it with one of the methods above.

For full model management instructions (pulling, storing, transferring
models) see @ref{Model Management}.


@node Cloning Codebud
@section Cloning Codebud
@cindex cloning, repository

@example
git clone https://github.com/mkhellat/codebud.git
cd codebud
@end example

The repository layout:

@example
agent/          Core agent (planner, executor, safety, tools, memory)
config/         Safety policy JSON files
data/           Embedding index and memory snapshots
docs/           This manual (GNU Texinfo)
openclaw/       OpenClaw skill wrapper
tests/          Pytest test suite
run_agent.py    CLI entry point
@end example


@node Python Environment
@section Python Environment
@cindex virtual environment
@cindex pip install

Create and activate a virtual environment:

@example
python -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
@end example

Your shell prompt will show @samp{(.venv)} when the environment is
active.  Install Codebud in editable mode together with dev dependencies:

@example
pip install -e ".[dev]"
@end example

This installs:
@itemize
@item @code{openai}, @code{requests}, @code{tiktoken} --- runtime deps
@item @code{pytest}, @code{ruff} --- dev deps
@item the @command{codebud} CLI entry point (maps to @code{run_agent:main})
@end itemize

To deactivate the environment later:

@example
deactivate
@end example

To reactivate in a new shell:

@example
source .venv/bin/activate
@end example


@node Verifying the Install
@section Verifying the Install
@cindex verification

@subsection Run the test suite

@example
pytest -q
@end example

All tests should pass.  No Ollama connection is needed for the tests.

@subsection Smoke-test the agent

Pull the recommended model if you have not already (@pxref{Pulling a Model}),
then:

@example
OLLAMA_MODEL=qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M \
    python run_agent.py "list files in the current directory"
@end example

You should see a JSON response with @code{"status": "ok"} and a plan
array.  On a CPU-only laptop, expect to wait 4--6 minutes for the
first response while the model loads and processes the prompt.
Subsequent calls reuse the loaded model and are faster.

@subsection Troubleshooting

If the agent returns @code{"status": "plan_error"}, see
@ref{Troubleshooting} for common causes and fixes.
